"I see that if I get paid for such a piece of work, you'll get far better paid;
                     and so far we are in the same boat. But I'm like to be caught, and you'll be
                     sure to come off free."

"No, indeed no," she replied, earnestly. "You have always called me Alice; and
                     if you were to change now, I should think I had vexed or offended you. Besides,
                     it is your common habit. Do you not call my niece Celia?"

Sydenham, struck with the sagacity of these strictures, pondered the matter;
                     and meeting Ethan next day, invited him to spend the evening at his house.
                     There the conversation was renewed.

Terence kept his promise. His former companions were not a little surprised;
                     and one of them, a strapping young fellow, said that same evening, when Terence
                     announced to them his intentions:

The blush, which had been passing away, deepened again. But the girl struggled
                     for composure: "No, Miss Celia. Mrs. Mowbray's French class is broken up,
                     and—and it's expensive to take private lessons."
